2026-07-16 ROOT CAUSE FIX: this kit's AGENT-RUNBOOK said "set chokepoint TRUE", and shared/new-map.sh copies this kit into every new map, so all 9 stamped maps inherited an instruction that contradicts the artifact template's chokepoint==='yes' test. The research agents were not sloppy; they did what the runbook told them. Fixed the wording here and in all 9 copies, and added rule 7 to tools/check_data.py so a runbook can never again instruct the vocabulary that breaks the renderer. Note 01's runbook always said chokepoint=yes correctly: the kit was written fresh on 2026-07-14 and drifted from the map it was modeled on. Verified by mutation: restoring the old kit wording turns the gate red and names this file.

2026-07-21 THREE CHECKS THAT ONLY EXIST BECAUSE A CLEAN RESULT LIED. Reflection pass, applied repo-wide.

RULE 9, cross-map contradictions: the same company at the same fiscal year must carry the same figures in
every map. Specified in the approved 2026-07-20 plan and NEVER BUILT until today -- an approved plan item
silently did not land and nothing noticed. The exposure is created by tools/reuse_costed.py and grows with
it: 04 inherits 12 rows from 01, and when 05 inherits from three maps a figure corrected in one and stale
in another is invisible, because BOTH rows are sourced and both pass rule 1. Aliases honoured, so a
contradiction between "Micron" and "Micron Technology" still counts.

R7, citation recency: verify_sources.py now leaves data/_verified.json and review.py reads it. Measured
before wiring: R7 fired on all three Mapped maps -- 82 costed rows whose citations nothing had ever
fetched, which is exactly the state that hid a row costed from the wrong company. After verifying, 02 and
04 went silent and 01 correctly reports PARTLY verified (38/41; the three failures are already gaps).

🔴 SCOPE FOOTERS, and this is the one that matters. review.py printed "No advisory findings: nothing is
presented as more settled than its evidence supports" -- a REPO-WIDE claim -- from a checker that opens
three of five data files and has never fetched a URL. I read my own clean output as completeness and
reported it that way; only Keaton asking "are we leaving work behind?" surfaced it. Both review.py and
gate.sh now state what they did NOT examine, on every run. The scope list is DERIVED from the same
constant run() loads, so the two cannot drift -- a hand-typed "we checked X, Y, Z" is a copy, and copies
rot. A clean result that does not name what it did not look at is a false claim you will believe.

⚠ AND THE WIRING TEST HAD TO GROW. Rule 8 got an end-to-end case on 2026-07-20 after its call-site mutant
survived a green suite. Rule 9 shipped hours later WITHOUT one, and its call-site mutant survived too --
the same failure, because the fix had been made per-rule instead of general. One fixture now proves every
run()-level rule is REACHABLE. Separately: a mutation that silently never applies is indistinguishable
from one that survives, so every mutant here asserts the file actually changed before drawing a verdict.
